column2: Do you relate to the problems of negative self-attention?
column3: What do you tend to pay attention to when you feel anxious in a social situation?
column4: Could you share a bit more about how you experience the relationship between anxiety and attention?

column3: My negative thoughts, unpleasant bodily sensations
My body language, how I’m standing, what I’m doing with my arms, if I’m staring, how my voice sounds, any hints of expression on the other person’s face
How I look, am I funny, do they think I’m stupid, do they think I’m not normal
How unhappy I am and that the situation making me anxious will get worse
How rubbish I feel and how people are thinking I’m stupid
The fact I am not making eye contact, my body language, my appearance
My posture, the way I look
All the things I may have done wrong
How I sound, how I look
My whole body, I’m anxious about the way I look
Noises around me, whether what I’m saying is interesting/engaging
How I look and people staring
I worry about what they are thinking about what I have said or what I come across like rather than focusing on their reaction to me or how they respond fully.
How I look and how people see me
How I stutter, how I avoid eye contact and look up, whether I’m saying the right thing
What I’m saying and how I look
I always pay attention to how I might come across to other people. If they can see me shaking or are paying a lot of attention to my speech mistakes.
Sweating, blushing, how my skin looks
The way I am speaking and whether I have been speaking too much or too little
Whether I have been talking for too long, or whether I’ve been too quiet and that I need to say something
How I’m fidgeting and if anyone notices.
My own thoughts of not knowing what to say, shaky hands and voice, making too much or too little eye contact
I focus too much on how I physically look and feel. I try not to show anxiety but that seems to use a lot of my focus
